<h2 id="what-is-xola">🎯 What Is Xola?</h2>

Xola is a booking and payment platform built specifically for tour operators, activity providers, and experience-based businesses. Unlike generic scheduling tools that treat a kayak tour the same as a haircut appointment, Xola understands the complexity of capacity management, variable pricing, guide assignments, and equipment tracking.

The platform launched in 2012 and has processed over $2 billion in bookings. Their client base ranges from single-operator walking tours to multi-location adventure companies running 50+ daily departures. The core value proposition is straightforward: handle every booking touchpoint from discovery to post-experience review collection, while integrating payments natively rather than bolting them on as an afterthought.

What separates Xola from competitors like FareHarbor, Peek, and Rezdy is their approach to customization. Where other platforms push you toward their templates, Xola provides building blocks. This flexibility comes at a cost—setup takes longer and the learning curve is real—but operators who need non-standard configurations will appreciate the difference.

<h2 id="our-experience">🔍 Our Experience Testing Xola</h2>

Our team has evaluated booking platforms across hundreds of tour and activity operations, from food tours in major metros to multi-day adventure outfitters. We've seen what breaks when operators scale from 500 to 5,000+ annual bookings, and we've watched promising tools collapse under the weight of real operational complexity.

We tested Xola across three distinct operation types: a urban walking tour company with 8 daily departures, a watersports rental business with equipment inventory tracking needs, and a multi-location escape room operator managing 12 rooms across 3 venues. This gave us visibility into how the platform handles different booking models, capacity constraints, and payment scenarios.

The initial setup took our team approximately 6 hours for the walking tour operation—significantly longer than simpler tools like Checkfront or even FareHarbor. However, that investment paid dividends once we started stress-testing edge cases. Complex pricing rules, blackout dates, guide availability conflicts, and weather-dependent rescheduling all worked without the workarounds we've had to build in other platforms.

The real test came when we simulated high-volume booking scenarios. Xola's infrastructure handled concurrent bookings without the inventory overselling issues we've encountered with less mature platforms. For operators who've experienced the nightmare of double-booked tours, this reliability alone justifies evaluation.

<h2 id="key-features">⚙️ Key Features That Matter for Operators</h2>

<h3>Abandoned Booking Recovery</h3>

This is Xola's killer feature, and the one that most directly impacts your revenue. When a customer starts checkout but doesn't complete payment, Xola automatically triggers a recovery sequence. The platform reports average recovery rates of 12-18% of abandoned carts, and our testing aligned with these numbers.

The system sends timed emails—typically at 1 hour, 24 hours, and 72 hours post-abandonment—with direct links to complete the booking. You can customize messaging, add discount incentives, and track which recovery strategies perform best. For a tour operator processing 500 monthly bookings with a 30% abandonment rate, recovering even 12% of those lost bookings adds 18 sales monthly without any additional marketing spend.

<h3>Dynamic Pricing Engine</h3>

Xola's pricing capabilities go beyond simple weekday/weekend differentials. You can build rules based on capacity utilization, booking lead time, customer segments, and promotional periods. Want to automatically increase prices when a tour hits 70% capacity? Done. Offer early-bird discounts that expire 14 days before departure? Built in.

For operators managing seasonal demand fluctuations, this dynamic pricing directly impacts margins. We've seen well-configured pricing rules add 8-15% to average booking value without reducing conversion rates.

<h3>Multi-Location Capacity Management</h3>

Tour operators expanding to multiple locations face a consistent challenge: unified visibility across all inventory without creating operational chaos. Xola handles this through a hierarchical structure that lets you manage at both the network and individual location level.

Staff can be assigned location-specific permissions, reports can aggregate or segment by venue, and customers can book across your entire operation through a single checkout flow. For [multi-location operators](/guides/multi-location-management), this centralized control prevents the spreadsheet chaos that often emerges during expansion.

<h3>Native Payment Processing</h3>

Xola processes payments directly rather than integrating with third-party processors. This creates a cleaner customer experience and simplifies reconciliation. The platform supports deposits, split payments, and automated balance collection—critical for operators booking experiences weeks or months in advance.

Refunds and modifications flow through the same system, creating audit trails that matter when disputes arise. The payment dashboard provides real-time visibility into processing status, chargebacks, and payout timelines.

<div class="callout-blue">
<strong>Operator Tip:</strong> Configure your deposit collection to require 50% at booking with balance due 7 days before the experience. This reduces no-shows significantly while maintaining customer flexibility. Xola's automated balance collection handles the follow-up so your team doesn't chase payments manually.
</div>

<h3>Guide and Resource Assignment</h3>

For operations with staff scheduling complexity, Xola's resource management prevents the double-booking disasters that plague growing tour companies. Guides, vehicles, equipment, and venues can all be tracked as resources with their own availability calendars.

When a booking comes in, the system automatically validates resource availability before confirming. This sounds basic, but we've seen operators using general-purpose scheduling tools manually track guide assignments in spreadsheets—a process that breaks spectacularly during peak season.

<h3>Distribution Channel Management</h3>

Xola connects to major OTAs including Viator, GetYourGuide, Expedia, and Google Things to Do. Inventory syncs in real-time, preventing overselling across channels. You can set channel-specific pricing, manage commission structures, and track which distribution partners actually deliver profitable bookings.

The channel analytics matter here. Not all OTA bookings are equal—commission rates vary, customer quality differs, and some channels deliver customers who never book direct in the future. Xola's reporting helps you make informed decisions about where to allocate inventory.

